<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the FIELD-LEVEL WRITE ACL that
    governs who may update the `assigned_agent` column on the `x_casemgmt_case`
    custom table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`. Per AAP Section
    0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) and AAP Section 0.5.1 ("Field-level ACL: write
    restricted to manager and agent-assigned"), this ACL grants write access
    to TWO populations and DENIES it to everyone else:
        1. Any user holding the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_manager`
           (unconditional - the manager is the case-management tier's
           delegation authority and may freely re-assign any case).
        2. Any user holding the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_agent` ONLY when
           `current.assigned_agent` already equals the current user's sys_id
           (i.e., the agent is the CURRENTLY-assigned agent on this case
           record). This narrowly scoped grant lets an assigned agent hand
           off, decline, or reassign their own work without granting them
           the ability to "grab" cases assigned to other agents.

    The two populations together implement the user-prompt mandate that an
    agent be operationally productive on their own caseload (including the
    ability to set `assigned_agent` to null or to a peer for handoff) while
    still preventing privilege escalation through self-assignment. The
    sibling field-level ACL `x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml`
    locks `assigned_group` writes to manager-only (no agent self-write at
    all) because group changes are higher-stakes (they cross team
    boundaries); this ACL deliberately differs by allowing self-write for
    agents to support the day-to-day handoff workflow.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.1 (File-by-File Transformation Plan, row for
        `acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml`):
            "Field-level ACL: write restricted to manager and agent-assigned"
        This file is the single artifact that materializes that single line
        in the transformation plan. The "manager" half is satisfied by the
        first branch of the script body below; the "agent-assigned" half by
        the second branch. The third (default) branch denies write to all
        other callers including viewers, unauthenticated portal traffic,
        and any future scoped roles that may be added.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix, full table reproduced verbatim from AAP):
            | Role                    | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_manager  |  Yes   | All               | All               |  Yes   |
            | x_casemgmt_case_agent    |  Yes   | Assigned only     | Assigned only     |  No    |
            | x_casemgmt_case_viewer   |  No    | All               | No                |  No    |
        The matrix above is enforced at TWO layers:
            (a) Table-level ACLs (sibling files
                `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_*.xml`,
                `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_*.xml`,
                `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_*.xml`,
                `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_delete_*.xml`) carry the row-level
                "All" / "Assigned only" predicates per role.
            (b) Field-level ACLs (THIS file plus
                `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml`)
                further narrow the WRITE scope on two specific columns
                (`assigned_agent` and `assigned_group`) so that even an
                agent who has passed the table-level write check still
                cannot poach assignments from peers and so that group
                changes remain a manager-only operation regardless of
                table-level write outcome.
        ServiceNow ACL evaluation requires BOTH the table-level write ACL
        AND the field-level write ACL to permit the operation for write
        to succeed; the most-restrictive ACL governs. Therefore an agent
        who can write to a case row (because they ARE assigned) still
        cannot change `assigned_agent` to a different user unless this
        field-level ACL also permits - and it does, via the second branch
        of the script below.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix, "Assigned only" definition):
            "Assigned only = cases where assigned_agent = current user OR
             assigned_group contains current user."
        That definition is the predicate encoded in the TABLE-LEVEL
        `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml` ACL (which gates
        whether an agent may write the case row at all). The FIELD-LEVEL
        predicate in THIS file is intentionally NARROWER than the table-
        level predicate: at the field level we require ONLY the
        "assigned_agent = current user" half (the strict
        already-the-assignee check) and DROP the
        "assigned_group contains current user" half. The reason is that
        a non-assigned agent who is merely a member of the assigned group
        should NOT be able to reassign the case to themselves or to anyone
        else - that would convert "team membership" into "self-grant
        authority". By requiring the agent to BE the current assignee at
        field-write time, the ACL preserves the manager's exclusive
        authority to make initial assignments while allowing the assigned
        agent to handle their own handoff lifecycle.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write;
             case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has
             full access."
        The middle clause ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases") is
        the central correctness criterion of THIS field-level ACL: a
        case_agent MUST NOT be able to set `assigned_agent` to themselves
        on an unassigned case, because doing so would let an agent
        unilaterally take ownership of any case in the system - the very
        definition of "accessing unassigned cases" the gate forbids. The
        script below denies writes by case_agent on any record where
        `current.assigned_agent` does not already equal the current
        user's sys_id; in particular, on a record where
        `current.assigned_agent` is null (an unassigned case), the
        comparison yields false and the agent is denied write access to
        the field. Only the manager - whose role grant bypasses the
        record-level check entirely - may make the initial assignment.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This file is one of the two field-level ACLs called out in
        that pattern statement; the other is
        `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml`. Together
        the two field-level ACLs encode the layered defense described in
        the AAP: table-level grants mediate ROW visibility, and field-
        level grants further constrain WRITE on the assignment columns.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "ArkCase resolves privileges via
        ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.getRolesToPrivileges() (a
        Map<String, List<Object>> bound from application.rolesToPrivileges
        configuration), enforced at URL/method level by
        AcmPluginUrlPrivilege. The target replaces this with three scoped
        roles ..., each governed by table-level ACLs (read, write, create,
        delete) and field-level ACLs on assigned_group / assigned_agent."
        This file is the second of the two field-level ACLs referenced in
        that statement.
      - Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map) - relationship to the
        Open -> In Progress transition:
            | Open | In Progress | assigned_agent populated AND member of
                                   assigned_group | Surface form-level error |
        The state-machine flow `../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml`
        and `../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml` (with subflow
        `../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml`) require
        `assigned_agent` to be populated before the Open -> In Progress
        transition can succeed. The MANAGER must populate `assigned_agent`
        through the form, since they are the only role guaranteed to be
        able to set it on a previously-unassigned case (the field-level
        ACL in this file denies the agent the ability to self-assign).
        Once an agent IS assigned by a manager, that agent may then
        reassign to a peer for handoff (the second branch of the script
        below allows this) - but they cannot bootstrap their own
        assignment. This is the workflow corollary of the
        privilege-escalation prevention encoded in this ACL.
      - Section 0.7.1 (Refactoring-Specific Rules and Requirements):
            "Enforce the exact role x CRUD matrix. Three scoped roles ...
             ACLs MUST be authored at table level AND field level for
             assigned_group and assigned_agent."
        This file is the field-level ACL for `assigned_agent`; the
        sibling file `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml`
        is the field-level ACL for `assigned_group`. Together with the
        eight table-level ACLs in this folder, they materialize the
        "table level AND field level" requirement.

    Why this ACL allows agent self-write where assigned_group_field_acl.xml
    does NOT:
      The two field-level ACLs in this folder differ in exactly one design
      choice: should the assigned agent be able to change the field
      themselves?
        - For `assigned_group`: NO. Group changes cross team boundaries,
          re-route cases between operational organizations, and have
          downstream implications for SLA, routing rules, and notification
          chains. These are fundamentally management decisions, not
          operational ones. An agent who is reassigning their own case to
          a different group is effectively making a routing decision that
          should require manager review. Hence
          `assigned_group_field_acl.xml` restricts write to the manager
          role only.
        - For `assigned_agent` (THIS FILE): YES, but ONLY when the agent
          is the currently-assigned agent. The handoff use case is core to
          day-to-day operations: an agent on PTO needs to hand off active
          cases; an agent reassigning a misrouted case to a colleague who
          is the SME; an agent declining an assignment that conflicts
          with prior commitments. These are ALL operational decisions
          that should not require manager involvement to execute. As
          long as the agent is operating ON their OWN caseload (the
          self-write check), they may freely transfer ownership.
      Both files share the manager-allowed branch (a manager can change
      either field unconditionally). They differ in the agent branch:
      `assigned_group_field_acl.xml` has no agent branch (manager-only);
      THIS file has an agent branch with the "currently-assigned" check.

    Why <advanced>true</advanced> is REQUIRED (CRITICAL):
      The ServiceNow ACL evaluator only invokes the <script> body when
      <advanced> is true. With <advanced>false</advanced>, the platform
      evaluates only the <condition/> encoded query (which is empty here)
      and the <roles> field, granting write to ANY user holding EITHER
      `x_casemgmt_case_manager` OR `x_casemgmt_case_agent` regardless of
      assignment state. This would directly violate AAP Section 0.5.6
      ("Assigned only" for agent) and AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 3
      ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases"). A non-assigned agent
      would be able to set `assigned_agent` to themselves and immediately
      gain "assigned only" table-level write authority on an arbitrary
      case - the privilege-escalation vector this ACL is designed to
      prevent. Setting advanced=true ensures the manager-or-assigned
      predicate in the CDATA script body is actually evaluated for every
      field-write attempt; setting it to false would silently disable
      this defense in depth.

    Why BOTH roles must appear in <roles> (CRITICAL):
      ServiceNow's ACL evaluator first filters candidate ACLs by role:
      only ACLs whose <roles> field contains a role the current user
      holds are considered for evaluation. Therefore if the <roles> field
      listed only `x_casemgmt_case_manager`, the ACL would NEVER be
      evaluated for a case_agent (the agent's caller-context wouldn't
      match the role filter), and the script body's second branch would
      never run - effectively disabling the agent-self-write capability
      and reducing the ACL to "manager-only" (i.e., duplicating the
      assigned_group ACL). Conversely, if <roles> listed only
      `x_casemgmt_case_agent`, managers would be denied write access to
      `assigned_agent` whenever they happened to lack the agent role -
      breaking the manager's "full access" mandate from AAP Section 0.5.6.
      Therefore BOTH roles MUST be listed in <roles>, and the script body
      then narrows further: managers pass unconditionally, agents pass
      only when self-assigned, all other holders of either role
      (theoretically impossible if the role grants are managed correctly)
      are denied by the default-false branch.

    Why the script uses gs.getUser().hasRole(...) instead of relying on
    the <roles> field alone:
      The <roles> field is a UNION filter (the user must hold ANY of the
      listed roles for the ACL to be considered). It cannot distinguish
      WHICH role caused the ACL to be considered. The script body's
      first branch must therefore use gs.getUser().hasRole(
      'x_casemgmt_case_manager') to confirm the caller is in the manager
      population BEFORE granting unconditional write; only if the manager
      check fails does the second branch evaluate the agent + self-write
      path. Without the explicit hasRole() check, an agent (who passed
      the union filter on case_agent) would be incorrectly granted the
      manager's unconditional branch.

    Edge cases handled by the script body:
      - current.assigned_agent IS NULL (unassigned case): the comparison
        `current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID()` evaluates to false
        (null is not equal to a sys_id string), so the agent branch
        denies. Only managers can set assigned_agent on a previously-
        unassigned case. THIS IS THE PRIMARY ANTI-SELF-GRABBING DEFENSE.
      - current.assigned_agent is a different user's sys_id: the
        comparison fails for any agent except the one whose sys_id
        matches; that one passes. Other agents (peers on the case's
        group, other agents on a different case, etc.) are denied.
      - User holds both case_manager and case_agent roles (unusual but
        possible): the manager branch fires first and grants
        unconditional write; the agent branch is short-circuited. This
        is the desired behavior - the user effectively operates at the
        higher-privilege role level when both are held.
      - User is admin (out-of-the-box ServiceNow admin role): the
        admin_overrides=true setting on this ACL allows admin to bypass
        ALL ACL checks, including this one. Admin retains the ability
        to override the field for troubleshooting or repair purposes.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map&lt;String, List&lt;Object&gt;&gt; rolesToPrivileges`)
        keyed by the property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. The class
        declares the constant `ROLES_TO_PRIVILEGES_PROP_KEY =
        "application.rolesToPrivileges"` and exposes the map via
        `@MapValue(value = "application.rolesToPrivileges")
        getRolesToPrivileges()`. In that model, FIELD-level write
        restrictions did not exist as a first-class concept; they had
        to be re-implemented per-field as imperative checks inside Spring
        service classes (e.g., a CaseFile setter would bracket the
        assignment with role-aware logic). The ServiceNow target replaces
        that scattered imperative model with a single declarative,
        scoped, field-level ACL whose scripted condition body carries
        the "manager-or-assigned" predicate. This XML record is the
        direct equivalent of the (case_manager + case_agent self-assign,
        WRITE, assigned_agent column) cell in the conceptual ArkCase map.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        `addRolesPrivileges(...)`, `removeRolesPrivileges(...)`). The
        service held injected dependencies on UserDao,
        ApplicationRolesConfig, ApplicationPrivilegesConfig,
        ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig,
        ConfigurationPropertyService,
        CollectionPropertiesConfigurationService, and
        FunctionalAccessService - a complex Spring/JPA stack that managed
        the role <-> privilege relationship at runtime. All of this Java
        service surface is replaced in the ServiceNow target by the
        platform's built-in sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted
        privilege resolver is needed. ArkCase's per-field write
        restrictions on sensitive columns required custom @PrePersist /
        @PreUpdate JPA listeners or aspect-oriented interceptors; the
        ServiceNow scoped equivalent is THIS field-level ACL XML record,
        which is declarative and centrally managed by the platform's ACL
        engine without any custom interceptor code.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package source =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table-and-column `x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent`
        (not any OOB table or any global column), and <roles> references
        the scoped roles `x_casemgmt_case_manager` and
        `x_casemgmt_case_agent`. Zero global writes from this file.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name
        / source-attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The CDATA
        script body uses gs.getUserID() (returns the runtime user's
        sys_id, not a literal) and current.assigned_agent (a GlideRecord
        field reference resolved by the platform at request time, not by
        literal). Role names inside hasRole() calls are also resolved by
        name lookup against the OOB sys_user_role table at runtime. The
        <sys_id> below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (32-char lowercase hex, MD5 of the canonical identifier
        "x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent.write.manager_or_assigned", a
        stable canonical key for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-
        reference to any other record. Computing the sys_id
        deterministically guarantees the ACL is re-applyable / idempotent
        across fresh PDIs and round-trip Update Set previews per AAP
        Section 0.7.3 Gate 7. The MD5 result is
        3719a93101a32c5e06c9907fbcfa8d03, computed once at authoring time
        and committed verbatim below; any reauthoring of this file must
        reproduce the same canonical key string and the same MD5 output
        to preserve idempotency.
      - Field-level (NOT table-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent`
        WITH a literal dot separator between table and column. This is
        the ServiceNow convention for field-level ACLs and distinguishes
        this record from the eight sibling table-level ACLs whose <name>
        is just `x_casemgmt_case` (no dot, no column).
      - Operation = write: corresponds exactly to the field-level write
        restriction described in AAP Section 0.5.1's row for this file.
        There are NO field-level read ACLs on x_casemgmt_case for any role
        (per AAP Section 0.5.6 only assigned_group and assigned_agent
        have any field-level ACLs at all, and those are write-only
        restrictions). There are NO field-level create or delete ACLs
        because those operations target rows, not fields.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern allowing the
        platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL for troubleshooting,
        repair, or seed-data operations. The seed script
        ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js runs as admin to populate demo
        cases (per AAP Section 0.7.4); admin's ability to set
        assigned_agent during that seed pass depends on this override.
        The admin override does NOT widen non-admin role privileges; it
        only allows the platform-level admin role to bypass the per-
        record predicate.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = true: the script body below IS evaluated at every
        write attempt against the assigned_agent column (see "Why
        advanced=true is REQUIRED" rationale above).
      - condition (empty): no encoded-query condition is set; the entire
        access predicate lives in the scripted body. ServiceNow ACLs
        evaluate condition AND script (both must permit when both are
        present); leaving condition empty defers all logic to the script.
      - type = record: this is a row-level (record-level) field ACL, not
        a UI/REST/SOAP-flavored one. The platform's record evaluator
        invokes this ACL during any GlideRecord update path that touches
        the assigned_agent column.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (resolves the table half of
          <name>x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent</name>)
        - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent.xml (resolves the
          column half of <name>x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent</name>; the
          field-level ACL cannot be applied until the field exists in
          sys_dictionary)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml (resolves
          the first entry in <roles> by role-name lookup at apply time)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml (resolves the
          second entry in <roles> by role-name lookup at apply time)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_*.xml
          (the demo manager and demo agent's write tests during round-trip
          verification depend on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml (demo cases are
          inserted by the seed pass; this ACL governs subsequent demo-
          time writes to the assigned_agent column)
        - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml,
          ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml,
          ../flows/sub_flows/validate_open_transition.xml,
          ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml (Flow
          Designer flows fire on update; their inline GlideRecord writes
          to assigned_agent during state transitions are filtered through
          this ACL when run by a logged-in agent or manager - the flows
          must not execute before the ACL is applied or unauthorized
          assigned_agent writes could leak through during update-set
          apply)

    Composition with the table-level WRITE ACLs:
      A write to the assigned_agent field requires BOTH:
        (a) The table-level write ACL on x_casemgmt_case to permit the row
            update (one of `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_manager.xml`,
            `../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml`, or admin
            override), AND
        (b) THIS field-level ACL to permit the column update.
      Concrete walk-throughs:
        * Manager writes assigned_agent on any case: (a) write_manager
          ACL grants unconditionally; (b) this ACL grants unconditionally
          via the manager branch. PERMITTED.
        * Currently-assigned agent reassigns themselves OFF a case
          (sets assigned_agent to a peer's sys_id): (a)
          write_agent_assigned ACL grants because assigned_agent ==
          current user; (b) this ACL grants via the agent self-write
          branch (assigned_agent at write time still equals current user).
          PERMITTED.
        * Currently-assigned agent declines an assignment (sets
          assigned_agent to null): (a) write_agent_assigned grants
          because pre-update assigned_agent == current user; (b) this
          ACL grants via the agent self-write branch (pre-update
          assigned_agent == current user). PERMITTED.
        * Non-assigned agent attempts to self-assign by setting
          assigned_agent to themselves on an unassigned case:
          (a) write_agent_assigned ACL DENIES because
          assigned_agent (null) != current user, and the group-membership
          check on the table-level ACL also fails (an unassigned case
          might have a group, but membership alone doesn't grant write
          on this column - the FIELD-LEVEL grant requires the strict
          assignee match). The write fails at the table level and never
          reaches this ACL. DENIED.
        * Non-assigned agent who IS in the assigned_group attempts to
          claim a case by setting assigned_agent to themselves:
          (a) write_agent_assigned grants because the group-membership
          half of "Assigned only" passes; (b) THIS ACL DENIES because
          the agent branch requires the strict pre-update
          assigned_agent == current user check, which fails. DENIED.
          THIS IS THE PRIMARY DEFENSE the ACL provides over the
          table-level ACL alone.
        * Viewer attempts to write assigned_agent: (a) NO write ACL
          grants the viewer role; the row update fails at the table
          level and never reaches this ACL. DENIED.
      The above walk-throughs are reproduced step-by-step in the manual
      ../scripts/round_trip_verify.md procedure.

    Difference from sibling field-level ACL (assigned_group):
      vs ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml:
        - <name>          x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent
                                            vs x_casemgmt_case.assigned_group
        - <roles>         x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent
                                            vs x_casemgmt_case_manager
        - <advanced>      true              vs (manager-only ACLs are
                                                typically advanced=false
                                                because they have no
                                                conditional logic)
        - <script>        manager-or-assigned-agent body
                                            vs (empty - manager grant is
                                                unconditional)
        - <sys_id>        3719a93101a32c5e06c9907fbcfa8d03
                                            vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case.assigned_group.write.manager_only")
        - <sys_update_name> *_assigned_agent_field_acl
                                            vs *_assigned_group_field_acl
      The two field-level ACLs share their column-targeting structure
      (<name> = table.column, <type>=record, <operation>=write,
      admin_overrides=true) but diverge in roles/advanced/script per the
      design choice described above ("Why this ACL allows agent
      self-write where assigned_group_field_acl.xml does NOT").

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used verbatim per AAP convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"); ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id is concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier is used consistently across every artifact - including the role-name strings inside the CDATA
    script body. The deterministic sys_id below is computed against
    the `casemgmt` literal and remains stable across re-imports onto
    fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Field-level ACL: x_casemgmt_case_manager can always write assigned_agent; x_casemgmt_case_agent can write assigned_agent only if they are the currently-assigned agent on the case. Allows agent self-reassignment without permitting case-grabbing.</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case.assigned_agent</name>
        <operation>write</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.1: "Field-level ACL: write restricted to
    // manager and agent-assigned". Per AAP Section 0.5.6 Matrix and
    // Section 0.7.3 Gate 3 ("case_agent cannot access unassigned
    // cases"), this script must DENY by default and grant only to
    // (a) any case_manager, and (b) the currently-assigned case_agent.

    // Branch 1: case_manager - unconditional grant.
    // The manager is the case-management tier's delegation authority;
    // they may freely assign, reassign, or null-out the assigned_agent
    // column on any case in the scoped application.
    if (gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager')) {
        return true;
    }

    // Branch 2: currently-assigned case_agent - conditional grant.
    // The agent may modify assigned_agent (handoff, decline, reassign
    // to peer) ONLY when they are the currently-assigned agent on the
    // case at write time. The strict equality check against
    // gs.getUserID() prevents:
    //   - non-assigned agents from self-grabbing unassigned cases
    //     (current.assigned_agent is null - comparison yields false)
    //   - non-assigned agents from poaching other agents' cases
    //     (current.assigned_agent is a peer's sys_id - comparison
    //      yields false)
    //   - non-agent role holders from being granted via this branch
    //     (the hasRole() guard filters them out before the comparison)
    // The comparison `current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID()` works
    // in ServiceNow because GlideRecord reference fields auto-resolve
    // to their sys_id when compared as strings; this is the standard
    // pattern used throughout the platform's ACL conditions.
    if (gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_agent')) {
        if (current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID()) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    // Default: deny. Viewers, anonymous users, and any other role
    // populations fall through to this branch. Per AAP Section 0.5.6
    // case_viewer has Write=No on every column of x_casemgmt_case;
    // this default-deny implements that mandate at the field level.
    return false;
})();]]></script>
